SIMPLE: scurf
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scurf
<hw>Scurf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>scurf</ets>,
<ets>sceorf</ets>, or from Scand.; cf. Sw. <ets>skorf</ets>, Dan.
<ets>skurv</ets>, Icel. <ets>skurfur</ets>, D. <ets>schurft</ets>, G.
<ets>schorf</ets>; all akin to AS. <ets>scurf</ets>, and to AS.
<ets>sceorfan</ets> to scrape, to gnaw, G. <ets>sch⟦uum⟧rfen</ets> to
scrape, and probably also to E. <ets>scrape</ets>. Cf.
<er>Scurvy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Thin dry scales or scabs upon
the body; especially, thin scales exfoliated from the cuticle,
particularly of the scalp; dandruff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, the foul remains of anything
adherent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scurf</qex> is worn away of each committed crime.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything like flakes or scales adhering to a
surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There stood a hill not far, whose grisly top⟦br⟧
Belched fire and rolling smoke; the rest entire⟦br⟧
Shone with a glossy <qex>scurf</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Minute membranous scales on the
surface of some leaves, as in the goosefoot.</def>
<rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scurff</ent>⟦br⟧
